{"id":"astro-ph/0402441","submitter":"Claudio Dalla Vecchia","authors":"Claudio Dalla Vecchia (1), Richard Bower (1), Tom Theuns (1 and 2),\n  Michael Balogh (1), Pasquale Mazzotta (3) and Carlos S. Frenk (1) ((1) ICC,\n  University of Durham, (2) University of Antwerp, (3) Dipartimento di Fisica,\n  Universita' di Roma)","title":"Quenching Cluster Cooling Flows with Recurrent Hot Plasma Bubbles","comments":"12 pages, 7 figures, accepted for publication on MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1111/j.1365-2966.2004.08381.x","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The observed cooling rate of hot gas in clusters is much lower than that\ninferred from the gas density profiles. This suggests that the gas is being\nheated by some source. We use an adaptive-mesh refinement code (FLASH) to\nsimulate the effect of multiple, randomly positioned, injections of thermal\nenergy within 50 kpc of the centre of an initially isothermal cluster with mass\nM_200=3x10^(14) Msol and kT=3.1 keV. We have performed eight simulations with\nspherical bubbles of energy generated every 10^8 years, over a total of 1.5\nGyr. Each bubble is created by injecting thermal energy steadily for 10^7\nyears; the total energy of each bubble ranges from 0.1--3x10^(60) erg,\ndepending on the simulation. We find that 2x10^(60) erg per bubble\n(corresponding to a average power of 6.3x10^(44) erg/s) effectively balances\nenergy loss in the cluster and prevents the accumulation of gas below kT=1 keV\nfrom exceeding the observational limits of 30 Msol/yr. This injection rate is\ncomparable to the radiated luminosity of the cluster, and the required energy\nand periodic timescale of events are consistent with observations of bubbles\nproduced by central AGN in clusters. The effectiveness of this process depends\nprimarily on the total amount of injected energy and the initial location of\nthe bubbles, but is relatively insensitive to the exact duty cycle of events.\n","versions":[{"